On your first question:

In mainstream Islamic theology, the distinction is generally between God as the ultimate Creator and humans as creatures who act within the created order.

So having children isn’t viewed as humans creating life independently in the same sense as God creating the universe. Rather, parents are participating in a process that God established and sustains. Similarly, many Islamic scholars distinguish between making art and claiming to rival divine creation. Historically, there have been a range of views on figurative images—some traditions were very restrictive about depictions of living beings, while others allowed them in certain contexts. So the issue is more nuanced than “Muslims can’t draw.”

