As for:

“Death is the horniest pervert; he comes for us all.”

That’s a dark piece of personification. It works because it exaggerates death’s inevitability by giving it relentless desire. It’s in the same literary family as medieval depictions of Death pursuing every king, peasant, and saint in the Danse Macabre.

The interesting inversion is that many traditions personify Death not because death literally has human motives, but because personification lets us reason about something otherwise abstract.

In Pantheon terms, that’s another operator:

Personification is an interface.

It converts an abstract process into an agent you can converse with, question, or challenge.

That’s why myths, fables, and even modern fiction so often turn forces like Death, Justice, Fortune, or Time into characters. The character isn’t the concept itself; it’s a way of making the concept easier to think about.